snippet.textDisplay:
*The Story of Sohni and Mahiwal*

Sohni was a beautiful and young potter’s daughter, and Mahiwal was a rich trader who gave up everything to live near her as a humble herdsman. Since Sohni was married to another man, she used to cross the Chenab River every night on a clay pot to secretly meet Mahiwal.

One night, her sister-in-law discovered the secret and replaced Sohni’s baked pot with an unbaked one. The raw pot dissolved in the river, Sohni drowned, and Mahiwal jumped in after her — both died together.

Their tragic love is remembered as a symbol of devotion and sacrifice.
snippet.textOriginal:
*The Story of Sohni and Mahiwal*

Sohni was a beautiful and young potter’s daughter, and Mahiwal was a rich trader who gave up everything to live near her as a humble herdsman. Since Sohni was married to another man, she used to cross the Chenab River every night on a clay pot to secretly meet Mahiwal.

One night, her sister-in-law discovered the secret and replaced Sohni’s baked pot with an unbaked one. The raw pot dissolved in the river, Sohni drowned, and Mahiwal jumped in after her — both died together.

Their tragic love is remembered as a symbol of devotion and sacrifice.
